This paper discusses the effectiveness of algorithmic tools in assessing bias and reliability in written content, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL). Therefore, cs.CL is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of AI assistance, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML), making cs.AI another likely sub-category. The study involves human perception and behavior, which could fall under the categories of cybernetics (CY) and social and information networks (SI). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of the findings for future research, which could fall under the category of human-computer interaction (HC).
